WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.880
In this talk we want to go a little high level and we want to describe how we envision the

00:00:14.880 --> 00:00:23.280
future of Shiny and what we do to fulfill that future. My name is Filip, I'm the CEO

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:33.279
of Appsilon and together with me we have Marek, our CTO. So we want to share what Appsilon builds

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:38.799
to empower everyone to create spectacular Shiny apps.

00:00:43.520 --> 00:00:51.360
All right, so if you're still with us, I think we can guess that you love Shiny just as we do.

00:00:51.840 --> 00:00:59.439
I personally believe that Shiny is a unique piece of technology. It empowered thousands of

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:06.720
scientists and data scientists worldwide to share, first to create and then to share

00:01:07.839 --> 00:01:17.199
their analysis and useful tools easily. Through the years we've seen some unique examples,

00:01:18.160 --> 00:01:26.559
some crazy ones, starting from native iPad iOS applications, through software as a service,

00:01:27.279 --> 00:01:34.480
Shiny apps, ending up with offline Shiny applications, on and on and on.

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:42.800
Just through pandemic we created three publicly available dashboards

00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:52.080
which were mentioned in the press and on the given days they received significant traffic.

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:59.440
So I think that it is clear by now that Shiny is ready to be used in different environments,

00:01:59.440 --> 00:02:04.559
enterprise environment, internal environment, external environment.

00:02:06.559 --> 00:02:10.800
It is being used by governments, NGOs and business.

00:02:12.880 --> 00:02:23.279
But if your app is not basic, if it's not simple, your success is at risk. And there are

00:02:23.919 --> 00:02:30.960
certain constraints that every person that works with Shiny needs to be aware of.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:37.839
There are technical and operational challenges waiting for you ahead.

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:43.600
And we've seen some great apps fail.

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:54.960
If navigated correctly, these challenges can be resolved, risk can be avoided.

00:02:55.759 --> 00:03:01.839
And we think that here we've identified what makes Shiny app successful.

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:11.119
So, if you want to make a successful app, you need to make sure that people are going to use it

00:03:11.119 --> 00:03:25.520
and to be happy to use it. And right now, people really don't want to use slow or not great-looking

00:03:25.759 --> 00:03:35.039
Shiny app or any app. People's expectations are very high regarding the friendliness.

00:03:35.039 --> 00:03:39.839
I'm not saying your application is ugly. I just say some applications are.

00:03:41.039 --> 00:03:47.520
And the better it looks, the easier it is to use, the higher the chances of getting

00:03:48.080 --> 00:03:52.639
buy-in from the people who are going to use it at the end of the day.

00:03:53.600 --> 00:04:01.360
And we've seen some teams building apps for many months, struggling to have an impact,

00:04:01.919 --> 00:04:10.160
and apps being bigger and bigger, slower and slower, and apps getting harder to maintain

00:04:10.160 --> 00:04:20.160
every day. Of course, we've also seen teams which managed to create great apps. It is possible.

00:04:21.119 --> 00:04:29.279
But it's not always straightforward. And also, very often, it is not expertise

00:04:29.279 --> 00:04:46.320
of these certain people to work in such a way. So, either teams need to be either aware that

00:04:46.320 --> 00:04:50.480
they might lose speed of development because it's harder to maintain,

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:54.559
or they need to gain expertise in other domains which are not their main domain.

00:04:58.160 --> 00:05:06.959
On the other hand, our background is in – so, Appsilon was founded by people with a background

00:05:06.959 --> 00:05:15.200
in applied mathematics and software engineering. And we are attracted to R. We are attracted to

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:25.279
Shiny as software engineers. And we think that this is something we bring to a diverse community

00:05:26.959 --> 00:05:34.399
of our world. And we want to embrace our background. We've built, through the years,

00:05:35.519 --> 00:05:40.239
many different Shiny apps. We solved many different problems, some of them taking months

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:50.480
to getting resolved. And we think that we can share what we achieved.

00:05:53.600 --> 00:06:05.839
Mark? We believe that our background in software engineering and our tools that we've created

00:06:06.720 --> 00:06:14.079
can help – can be our way to contribute to our community. And this way, we can

00:06:15.679 --> 00:06:23.359
empower scientists, researchers, data scientists worldwide to create spectacular apps themselves.

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:30.000
We believe that this way, more apps can be created. They can be created faster. And also,

00:06:30.799 --> 00:06:42.480
together, we can encourage more people to try R and Shiny and kickstart their journey.

00:06:46.239 --> 00:06:56.399
This is one slide that I shared during my talk at a user conference in Toulouse. And at that time,

00:06:56.959 --> 00:07:07.200
I kind of embraced advantages of Shiny when compared to different technologies and

00:07:08.320 --> 00:07:20.480
alternatives. But I think the solution to building better Shiny applications also lies

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:26.079
in these other technologies. And as much as we have some advantages,

00:07:26.079 --> 00:07:33.359
we also need to recognize that certain other technologies can teach us how we can do better.

00:07:33.359 --> 00:07:53.760
So, with our mission statement being set, which is to empower data scientists to create

00:07:53.760 --> 00:08:01.519
spectacular Shiny apps, I will hand off now to Mark to show you some work that we've actually

00:08:01.519 --> 00:08:07.679
put into fulfilling on this mission and also to discuss our progress so far.

00:08:09.519 --> 00:08:16.239
Thank you, Filip. So, I'm very excited to share with all of you these new developments that we

00:08:16.239 --> 00:08:21.839
will be releasing. And if you have any questions, please post them in the question section and we

00:08:21.839 --> 00:08:28.480
will be happy to answer. So, a great UI is something that takes your Shiny app to an

00:08:28.480 --> 00:08:36.559
entirely new level. And we have heard great talks today from Tom and Shannon, obviously,

00:08:39.039 --> 00:08:44.239
from Pedro about custom styling, from Dominik, who mentioned lots of Shiny extensions.

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:52.479
So, there are a lot of great options already. However, looking at what is available in other

00:08:52.479 --> 00:08:58.719
technologies, they have not only Bootstrap and Semantic, for example. Actually, there are tons

00:08:58.719 --> 00:09:07.919
of libraries for user interfaces and so on. And not all of them are yet easily available for us

00:09:07.919 --> 00:09:16.239
in Shiny. So, we are changing a part of that today with two new packages, which are Shiny

00:09:16.239 --> 00:09:23.039
Fluent and Shiny React. And the main thing I want to talk about today is Shiny Fluent.

00:09:24.559 --> 00:09:32.400
So, Shiny Fluent lets you use Microsoft's Fluent UI in Shiny. But what is Fluent UI from Microsoft,

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:39.359
first of all? So, Fluent is a UI library from Microsoft that is used a lot in their software.

00:09:39.919 --> 00:09:47.280
If you use Fluent UI in your app, it can basically look like Microsoft's Excel

00:09:47.280 --> 00:09:53.359
or Outlook and so on. So, this means that your app gets a nice professional look,

00:09:53.919 --> 00:10:00.239
which is a great fit, particularly if your users are in large companies, and especially so

00:10:00.799 --> 00:10:07.280
if your company is already using Office and, for example, Power BI a lot. So, we've seen Shiny

00:10:07.280 --> 00:10:14.960
compete with Power BI quite a lot. And almost always, one of the points in favor of Power BI was

00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:19.280
a better interface. So, today we want to bring this to Shiny.

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:26.479
Right. So, let me open another page.

00:10:26.479 --> 00:10:38.479
Right. So, everything you see here is a Shiny application. It's completely coming from Shiny.

00:10:39.039 --> 00:10:46.400
And this is built using Fluent UI. This is actually a part of our documentation. So,

00:10:46.400 --> 00:10:51.599
you can browse all the components that are available in Shiny Fluent,

00:10:52.080 --> 00:11:01.119
like various kinds of buttons, for example. It's very configurable. So, you can

00:11:01.119 --> 00:11:08.719
really have a lot of room in defining easily using parameters, the appearance and the

00:11:08.719 --> 00:11:17.440
behavior of those buttons. You have lots of cool stuff like contextual menu,

00:11:17.919 --> 00:11:28.719
nice looking lists. I really like some of the features that Fluent provides for

00:11:29.280 --> 00:11:35.119
guiding your users through the application, especially for the first time,

00:11:35.760 --> 00:11:40.640
like the coach mark that can appear and contain some explanation.

00:11:40.640 --> 00:11:51.359
Of course, there are nice dialogue windows and so on. It's just all of it looks nice and

00:11:51.359 --> 00:12:01.440
is so powerful and configurable. Also, Shiny Fluent has a lot of components for which

00:12:03.039 --> 00:12:09.440
often in Shiny, we used to have to pull in other packages like custom packages

00:12:09.440 --> 00:12:19.599
to have some kind of nice input. So, a lot of this is already available within Fluent

00:12:20.479 --> 00:12:29.760
and via Shiny Fluent in Shiny. So, there's one problem though here, and it is that

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:38.880
Fluent is based on React. So, to get all of this appearance, you need to render it via React.

00:12:39.679 --> 00:12:46.000
And that's why we built Shiny React, which brings React to Shiny.

00:12:47.280 --> 00:12:52.000
And the story of Shiny React starts when you thought just about how cool it would be to

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:57.760
have a reliable and efficient way of using all the richness of the React ecosystem in

00:12:57.760 --> 00:13:04.000
our Shiny apps. Just think of it. There are so much great stuff. There's so much great stuff

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:09.440
available in React, like all the frameworks, material UI, Blueprint, Fluent, tons of components

00:13:09.440 --> 00:13:18.080
for charts, maps, and whatnot. And also, one thing that is super important is that

00:13:18.640 --> 00:13:27.599
Facebook's team has put a lot of effort into improving its performance. So, it's really fast.

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:36.640
So, it can make also our Shiny apps faster. And JavaScript developers have all of this because

00:13:36.640 --> 00:13:42.960
they use React. So, we should have that too. So, in one sentence, Shiny React aims to let you easily

00:13:42.960 --> 00:13:52.159
use React libraries in Shiny. And I'd like to thank authors of a package that was available

00:13:52.159 --> 00:13:59.440
earlier, which is React R, especially for some of the ideas that they have in their package,

00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:05.760
which helped us. And in our scenario and our goal, it just didn't work for us

00:14:07.440 --> 00:14:13.760
due to some of the limitations. And one example here is that React R seems to be focused more on

00:14:14.479 --> 00:14:24.000
making and porting individual components or just a few components and not necessarily

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:33.760
entire UI libraries. So, what's special about Shiny React? First of all, you can port entire

00:14:33.760 --> 00:14:40.559
UI libraries. And it's easy for Shiny app developers. The inputs that you get are

00:14:41.200 --> 00:14:46.960
really close, as close as possible to the Shiny API that we are used to.

00:14:49.919 --> 00:14:57.359
I think that was quite challenging to achieve is to give the ability to mix and nest Shiny in

00:14:57.359 --> 00:15:04.880
React and inside that have Shiny again, like outputs from Shiny and so on, so that we can

00:15:04.880 --> 00:15:11.760
still use all the Shiny components that we are used to. It also provides documentation for the

00:15:11.760 --> 00:15:19.119
components coming from the original packages, but inside the R documentation system,

00:15:19.840 --> 00:15:24.000
which is very useful. And basically, it solves a lot of practical challenges that

00:15:25.119 --> 00:15:32.239
you just don't have to think about. So, this is what made Shiny fluent possible.

00:15:32.880 --> 00:15:38.320
And I'm excited to see what other libraries can be made available this way.

00:15:39.599 --> 00:15:45.840
But let's go back to Shiny fluent. So, this is a most basic app. And what's special here is

00:15:47.200 --> 00:15:55.520
you just use the library. So, we load the package Shiny fluent. And then you just have to wrap your

00:15:55.520 --> 00:16:03.919
code with the React function call. And inside, you can use all the components that are taken

00:16:04.559 --> 00:16:13.520
from fluent. You can use all of their properties and so on. So, basically, this code gives you

00:16:13.520 --> 00:16:22.799
these two nice buttons. But so that you fully believe me, I'd like to do a quick live demo.

00:16:26.479 --> 00:16:35.599
So, this is an application that we built just in a couple of hours using fluent UI. It's, again,

00:16:35.599 --> 00:16:46.080
all Shiny. So, a scenario that we picked is that let's say we want to analyze how our sales

00:16:46.080 --> 00:16:55.280
department performs and which sales reps, sales representatives perform best. So, you can see here

00:16:56.080 --> 00:17:04.160
all those nice inputs that I think are very, very just pleasant to use.

00:17:06.239 --> 00:17:14.160
It's always an issue with late peakers. So, I really like how they solve this in fluent.

00:17:14.719 --> 00:17:25.839
And really nice components like this people picker, which can show you a lot of details about

00:17:29.920 --> 00:17:31.599
the people that you pick.

00:17:35.760 --> 00:17:42.560
A really nice list view. But what's also interesting is that what you can see here,

00:17:42.560 --> 00:17:49.439
this is a regular leaflet map, like inserted with a leaflet output. But this leaflet output is

00:17:49.439 --> 00:17:57.760
inside an entire structure, which was put here, not like we used to do, but by React.

00:17:58.560 --> 00:18:04.959
So, it's not obvious that this works, believe me. So, this is really cool that you can,

00:18:04.959 --> 00:18:09.520
this shows that you can embed what we already have in Shiny inside React.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:19.839
And then the same here with this Plotly plot. So, this is a truly live demo. Let's

00:18:20.400 --> 00:18:26.800
try to make a change to this app, add some functionality. Let's see if we succeed.

00:18:26.800 --> 00:18:35.920
And so, let's say we want to filter this list of deals closed by the sales reps.

00:18:36.319 --> 00:18:44.800
We want to filter out the smallest deals, like have some minimum limit for the amount of the deal.

00:18:47.040 --> 00:18:54.400
So, we can use, well, let's find some component that we want to use.

00:18:56.160 --> 00:19:00.319
So, we can pick Slider, for example. And we can see that Slider is just,

00:19:01.280 --> 00:19:08.000
we just need to insert a Slider and give it an input ID, as usually in Shiny.

00:19:09.680 --> 00:19:12.000
So, let's do that. Let's go to RStudio.

00:19:15.680 --> 00:19:20.640
So, we can go to where the filters are. This is our UI code.

00:19:20.640 --> 00:19:35.439
Right. So, we have the Slider. There's lots of configuration options. So, and you can just type,

00:19:37.199 --> 00:19:45.439
you know, type question mark Slider, and then you will get that in the documentation

00:19:45.439 --> 00:19:53.280
window, all the options available. But let's say we define a step of 100,000 and

00:19:53.280 --> 00:20:00.719
we give a label. We can configure how to format that. Right. So, this gives us already an input

00:20:00.719 --> 00:20:07.920
that we can use in our server part. So, now what we need to do is just to filter the items,

00:20:08.239 --> 00:20:18.800
filter the items based on the input value. And that should do it.

00:20:22.880 --> 00:20:31.119
Let's refresh the app. Right. And we have the Slider here.

00:20:31.599 --> 00:20:41.599
So, I think it looks really nice. It's just a really beautiful Slider, if a Slider can be

00:20:41.599 --> 00:20:51.199
beautiful. I just really like how it smoothly moves. Anyway, it's very consistent with the

00:20:51.199 --> 00:21:03.920
entire look. Right. We could add some debunks here. Anyway, as you can see, we can filter

00:21:05.040 --> 00:21:14.079
the deals just to the biggest ones. So, going back to the presentation.

00:21:15.040 --> 00:21:22.160
So, the good news is that all of this will be open source and we will be releasing this in the

00:21:22.160 --> 00:21:28.160
just in the coming weeks, starting with an early access group. So, if you're interested,

00:21:28.160 --> 00:21:34.560
please fill out the masterclass feedback form. The link will be at the end of this presentation.

00:21:35.839 --> 00:21:43.040
And make sure there's a checkbox which you can check to be in the early access group for Shiny

00:21:43.119 --> 00:21:49.359
Fluent. So, make sure to do that if you're interested in that. And you can already today

00:21:50.239 --> 00:21:56.880
open the app with a demo at this URL. All right.

00:21:58.640 --> 00:22:06.800
And so, the second area that I want to cover is developer tools. So, you may have seen August's

00:22:06.800 --> 00:22:15.520
great talk about best practices just a while before. And what she did was she shared a lot

00:22:15.520 --> 00:22:24.560
of best practices that we use in the community. And she did this in a non-opinionated way. So,

00:22:24.560 --> 00:22:29.119
no matter what technology, there were some examples, but no matter what technology choices

00:22:29.119 --> 00:22:32.959
you make, you can still use these best practices. There are a lot of options.

00:22:33.920 --> 00:22:40.319
At the same time, at Appsilon, we are building patterns and development workflow tools

00:22:41.520 --> 00:22:47.920
that realize these best practices in a very opinionated way, which is, in our opinion,

00:22:49.599 --> 00:22:56.560
just works best in most projects. So, today, I'd like to share with you that we will be publishing

00:22:57.359 --> 00:23:05.760
kind of first of its kind Shiny application framework. So, a thing that runs on top of Shiny

00:23:05.760 --> 00:23:14.880
and lets you be more efficient for building production apps. So, there are a lot of areas

00:23:14.880 --> 00:23:21.199
that you can take care of to make your app work well in production. You don't necessarily have to

00:23:21.920 --> 00:23:30.160
take care of all of them. But if you do, it really, really increases your chances of success.

00:23:31.680 --> 00:23:38.800
So, over the years, we've built tools for all of these areas. And in the coming months,

00:23:38.800 --> 00:23:42.160
we will be gradually sharing them as a unified framework.

00:23:42.160 --> 00:23:52.079
So, why does this matter? Basically, all of the points from the previous slide matter,

00:23:52.079 --> 00:23:59.199
because ultimately, for apps that work in production, the users, your users depend on them.

00:24:00.880 --> 00:24:05.119
We need to ensure that they're, first of all, reliable and easy to maintain.

00:24:06.319 --> 00:24:09.199
But also for our projects to be successful, we need to do that,

00:24:10.160 --> 00:24:15.359
achieve maintainability and reliability while keeping the development velocity

00:24:16.400 --> 00:24:21.439
high, which keep the velocity that Shiny is famous for.

00:24:23.359 --> 00:24:27.520
So, just some examples of what you will get with the framework out of the box.

00:24:28.400 --> 00:24:36.959
Mature domain-driven application structure, end-to-end tests, like on this example of Cypress.

00:24:39.280 --> 00:24:47.280
Comprehensive, but easy to use dependencies management, like Olga mentioned. Data validation.

00:24:49.760 --> 00:24:56.400
So, what's really new here compared to existing solutions? I think there are three main things.

00:24:56.400 --> 00:25:00.479
First of all, it's a complete framework, a complete ecosystem covering,

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:07.760
giving you an option for all of the points that you need to think of.

00:25:08.079 --> 00:25:16.000
Then, it's just the fact that we bring best practices from other technologies

00:25:17.280 --> 00:25:24.880
in areas where as Shiny community, we can benefit most by learning from other technologies.

00:25:25.439 --> 00:25:35.199
And the third, you get all these best practices, not as knowledge, but as code.

00:25:35.839 --> 00:25:39.439
So, you can start your project from scratch with all the best practices included and

00:25:40.560 --> 00:25:45.920
you can learn what you, which parts you need, like you can learn each part that you need

00:25:46.560 --> 00:25:52.719
from the code that is already in your project and it's already working and you can learn from that.

00:25:55.359 --> 00:25:58.000
Right. So, back to Filip.

00:25:58.239 --> 00:26:10.079
Yes. So, our workflow and ShinyFluent and ShinyReact are going to be fully open-sourced.

00:26:11.199 --> 00:26:16.640
We are excited to share our frameworks and our way of work, but we think that sometimes

00:26:17.199 --> 00:26:25.760
frameworks are just not enough. They don't cut it on their own. And this is why we want to create

00:26:25.760 --> 00:26:36.400
another resource for our community. So, in other communities, if you want to create

00:26:36.400 --> 00:26:40.000
your WordPress page, if you want to create your e-commerce store,

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:49.520
if you want to create your static bootstrap website, you can grow thousands, maybe hundreds,

00:26:50.239 --> 00:26:55.760
depending on the use case, pre-made quality templates and layouts. You can choose,

00:26:57.599 --> 00:27:05.680
pick the one you like. You can download or buy and customize with a fraction of work necessary

00:27:05.680 --> 00:27:16.880
to build everything from scratch. And this is why we decided to do the same thing for

00:27:17.680 --> 00:27:22.079
our Shiny community. So, Mark.

00:27:28.400 --> 00:27:37.359
So, we decided to share some of our work. Our Shiny apps are often complimented for

00:27:37.680 --> 00:27:47.119
how they look, and we are quite proud about taking care of great design. We deeply care here

00:27:47.760 --> 00:27:58.400
about stuff being both easy to use and beautiful and useful. So, some of the layouts that were

00:27:58.400 --> 00:28:04.880
crafted by our engineers and designers are going to be available, some of them for free, some of

00:28:04.880 --> 00:28:18.000
them to buy on the platform that we are going to share with everyone. So, what did we promise

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:27.760
today? First, Shiny Fluent and Shiny React are going to be open source. You can create great

00:28:28.400 --> 00:28:35.040
enterprise-grade applications, especially for enterprise ecosystem with Shiny Fluent,

00:28:35.040 --> 00:28:45.199
and we should expect more React libraries being ported as R packages available to us.

00:28:46.319 --> 00:28:53.760
Second, we will open source a lot of our internal tools to empower the whole community

00:28:54.400 --> 00:29:01.599
to leverage what we've discovered in many of our projects, so that the whole community can

00:29:02.800 --> 00:29:09.599
move forward much faster. At least, we hope so. Third, we will help kick start

00:29:10.800 --> 00:29:17.439
hopefully more teams and more Shiny developers their own work with pre-made templates and layouts.

00:29:17.760 --> 00:29:24.800
All this we do because we want to empower data scientists and scientists and researchers

00:29:24.800 --> 00:29:32.160
worldwide to create more and better Shiny apps, so that, together, we can have more impact

00:29:32.800 --> 00:29:38.800
and help other people make wiser decisions for the data.

